1. Open Group Policy Management Console (GPMC) on your Windows Server and create a new GPO named 'PasswordPolicyDemo' that enforces a minimum password length of 8 characters. Link it to your test OU and verify the setting is applied using gpresult.
=> Open Group Policy Management Console (gpmc.msc via Run/Search).
Expand Forest → Domains → your domain (e.g., mycollege.local).
Right-click Group Policy Objects → New.
Name: PasswordPolicyDemo → OK.
Right-click the new GPO → Edit.
Navigate to:
Computer Configuration → Policies → Windows Settings → Security Settings → Account Policies → Password Policy.
Double-click Minimum password length.
Set it to 8 characters → OK.
Close the Editor.

Link the GPO:

Right-click the EventPlanners OU → Link an Existing GPO → Select PasswordPolicyDemo → OK.

Verify with gpresult:

On the DC or a domain-joined client: Open Command Prompt as admin.
Run: gpresult /h report.html /scope computer
Open the HTML report and check under Computer Configuration → Policies → Windows Settings → Security Settings → Account Policies → Password Policy for the 8-character minimum.

2. Configure a GPO to restrict access to the Control Panel for all users in a specific OU, similar to how public computers in a cybercafe or college lab prevent users from changing system settings.<br><br><em><strong>Hint:</strong> In the GPO, navigate to User Configuration > Administrative Templates > Control Panel and set 'Prohibit access to Control Panel and PC settings' to Enabled.</em>
=>In GPMC, right-click Group Policy Objects → New → Name: ControlPanelRestriction.
Right-click the new GPO → Edit.
Navigate to:
User Configuration → Policies → Administrative Templates → Control Panel.
Double-click Prohibit access to Control Panel and PC settings.
Set to Enabled → OK.
Close the Editor.
Link this GPO to the EventPlanners OU

3. Edit your 'PasswordPolicyDemo' GPO to enable account lockout after 3 invalid login attempts and set the lockout duration to 10 minutes. Run gpupdate /force on a client PC and test the lockout by entering the wrong password.
=>In GPMC, right-click PasswordPolicyDemo → Edit.
Go to:
Computer Configuration → Policies → Windows Settings → Security Settings → Account Policies → Account Lockout Policy.
Configure these settings:
Account lockout threshold: 3 invalid logon attempts.
Account lockout duration: 10 minutes.
Reset account lockout counter after: 10 minutes (recommended matching duration).

Click OK on each.
Close the Editor.

Apply and Test:

On a domain-joined client (or DC), run: gpupdate /force.
Log off/on or wait for policy refresh.
Test lockout: Attempt to log in with one of the users

